*9: Justification of your recommendation\
  My reason for rejection is that you state that "In order to evaluate the space\
optimization procedure and obtain the best error rates, we also evaluate the\
complete set of 2d-1 possible distances combinations on the testing dataset Stest\
for each criteria independently. Hence, we will separate our evaluation of the\
results between the best results obtained (across all distances combinations) and\
the space automatically selected by the optimization procedure."\
I read this as saying you optimised the parameters on the test data and report the\
best results. If this is true, it is a meaningless comparison and should be removed.\
If I have misunderstood, you should clarify better. I reject this paper assuming\
there is bias in the reported results and that the last column of table III presents\
highly over optimistic picture of the algorithm. If I have misunderstood this, I\
would raise this paper to marginal. \
\
The HVs results are better than DTW on 31 data sets, worse on 13. This is a good\
result. However, my main reason for being less enthusiastic about this paper is that\
after reading the description of the algorithm twice I'm still not clear how the\
classifier works. Several classifiers based on something called MOTS (which is\
described in a paper I'm not allowed to see!) are introduced, including NP-MOTES,\
HV-MOTS etc, without a full algorithmic description. The hyper volume definition is\
apparently recursive (second column of III.B), and the classification algorithm\
given in (4) is parameterised in an unclear way. \
\
\
 Given the abstract motivates "results in TSC accuracy seem to underline that not\
much progress has been done ... over the past decade", the paper ignores recent\
work on alternative elastic measures and methods of combining them in ensembles\
which do actually do significantly better than DTW\
\
