  I am somewhat ambivalent about this paper. On one hand it (mostly) well written\
and has lot of experiments. However, most of the ideas appear in the authors\
journal paper from last year [a].\
\
Ultimately, the paper proposes to 
\f3 \uc0\u65533 
\f0 measure the nearest neighbors under lots of\
measures, and combine using Pareto ideas to compute the answer
\f3 \uc0\u65533 
\f0 . However, if you are\
going to compute 
\f3 \uc0\u65533 
\f0 lots of measures
\f3 \uc0\u65533 
\f0 , there are other ways to combine them. These\
possibilities are not discussed, and this is a real weakness\
\
Moreover, from a practical point of view, on a real implemented system, using\
multiple measures will be very slow. DTW and ED can be implemented very efficiently,\
in amortized O(1) time (on a sliding window query), but it is less clear that\
ERP,LCSS,EDR,OSB,CDM can.\
\
The ideas are not expressed as intuitively as one might like. The explanation\
(reveiw) of 2d Pareto optimialy is good, after that, it gets a little hard to\
understand. \
